  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Lamplight Temple
  author: Kim Dun-si
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The temple presses down upon the endless waves,
    And standing high, I seem to float mid-ocean.
    The bamboo shadows shift from sparse to dense,
    While resting my head, the rapids sing—now soft, now loud.

    In silent night the incense in the scripture tower grows cold,
    Beneath the moon the guest room's hemp robe turns cool.
    Yet such fair beauty cannot hold me here—
    I must hurry on, all day bewildered, racing after rice.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Lamplight Temple (燈明寺) is situated on a peninsula or promontory overlooking water, creating the effect of isolation described in the opening couplet.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'scripture tower' (經樓) refers to a tower within the temple where Buddhist scriptures are kept.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet employs a poignant turn, contrasting the serene natural beauty with the speaker's inability to remain due to worldly obligations and the constant struggle for survival.
